> Patrick learned how to make this dish whilst filming in the beautiful coastal town of Catania and, in a fairly risky move, he has decided to recreate it with a few of his own flavours. Italians are fiercely protective of their recipes so, for his sake, let's keep this one under our hats!

== Caponata ==

Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Remove the stalk top from the @aubergine{1}, cut in half
lengthways and then chop into 2cm cubes. Chop the @celery stick{1} into ½cm chunks. Peel and
grate all but one of the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve, then remove the
cores from the @green pepper{½}(chopped) and @bell pepper{1}(chopped) and chop into 2cm pieces.
We like our @olives{15} whole, but chop them if you prefer!

Spread the aubergine and peppers in a single layer on a lined #baking tray{}. Drizzle with
@olive oil{} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast on the top shelf of your oven until
soft and a little crispy around the edges, ~{20-25%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Heat a splash of oil in a #frying pan{} on medium heat. Once hot, add the celery with a pinch
of salt and a grind of pepper.

When the celery is soft, after about ~{5%minutes}, add the garlic. Cook for ~{1%minute} more.
Add the @Tuscan pork sausage{250%g} and use a #wooden spoon{} to break it up. Cook for
~{5%minutes}. Pour in the @chopped tomatoes{1}(diced), then fill the tin(s) a quarter with
water and add to the pan. If you are cooking for three people, add the @?tomato puree{}. Add
the olives, @white wine vinegar{1} and another pinch of salt. Stir, then simmer until the
mixture is thickened, ~{10-15%minutes}.

== Garlicky Ciabatta ==

Once the veggies are cooked, add them to the caponata. Turn your grill to high. Cut the
@ciabatta{1} in half (as if you were making a sandwich), place on the baking tray and toast
on each side until golden brown. Once toasted, cut the remaining garlic clove in half and
rub it across the cut side of each ciabatta. Drizzle over the @olive oil{} and season with a
pinch of salt.

When your caponata has thickened, serve it in #bowls{} with the garlicky ciabatta on the
side. It can be eaten with cutlery or by using the bread as an edible shovel. Enjoy!